  "articleSummary": "The article argues that `Error.stack` is fundamentally unreliable for debugging async JavaScript because `await` suspends execution, clearing the call stack and losing causal history. It critiques V8’s `--async-stack-traces` flag as a costly (30% slowdown) and noisy fix, then promotes `AsyncLocalStorage` as the production-ready solution for preserving request context across async boundaries. Written in a conversational, slightly frustrated tutorial tone for Node.js developers, it uses metaphors like “cryogenic freezer” for the microtask queue and contrasts “stack” (genealogy) with “trace” (causality). The core thesis: stop trusting stack traces; instead, attach structured context (e.g., request IDs) via `AsyncLocalStorage` and use OpenTelemetry for causal chains.",
